It also follows that since the vacuum electric permittivity ε0 (also known as the electric constant), the characteristic impedance of vacuum Z0, and the admittance of vacuum Y0 are equal to 1/μ0c2, μ0c, and 1/μ0c, respectively, the values of ε0, Z0, and Y0 must now also be determined experimentally, and are affected by the same relative standard uncertainty as μ0 since c is exactly known. The product ε0μ0=1/c2 and quotient Z0/μ0=c remain exact. At the time of adopting the present definition of the ampereampere (A









), μ0 was equal to 4π×10−7⁢H/m









 with a relative standard uncertainty of 2.3×10−10.

